# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: virginia-house-of-delegates
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The **164th Virginia General Assembly**, consisting of members who were elected to the Senate in 2023 and the House of Delegates in 2025, convened on January 14, 2026.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Democrats retained a majority in the Virginia Senate and expanded their majority in the House of Delegates, with Democratic former State Senator Ghazala Hashmi becoming the next Lieutenant Governor.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The 2026 session began on January 14 and is set to adjourn on March 14, 2026.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The 2024 special session that was called in the previous term of the Virginia General Assembly by Governor Glenn Youngkin briefly ran concurrently into the 2026 session until it was adjourned on January 15, 2026.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The leadership structure remained largely unchanged from the previous assembly, with Democrats maintaining control of both chambers, by 21-19 in the Senate, and 64-36 in the House.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] In the House of Delegates, Don Scott was re-elected as Speaker on January 14, 2026.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Committee assignments were updated at the start of the session, with key committees such as Appropriations, Finance, and Privileges and Elections reflecting Democratic priorities.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The regular session commenced on January 14, 2026, with key procedural resolutions adopted, including the schedule for bill introductions (deadline January 23, 2026) and crossover (February 17, 2026).
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] At the end of the regular session, on March 14, 2026, 3,646 bills had been introduced, with committees actively hearing legislation ahead of the crossover deadline.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Governor Abigail Spanberger delivered her first address to a joint session on January 19, emphasizing affordability, bipartisanship, and priorities such as healthcare costs, housing, and gun safety.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Governor Spanberger presented her budget proposal on December 17, 2025, focusing on affordability measures, including investments in education, healthcare, and housing.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Budget hearings were held on January 2, 2026.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The House Appropriations and Senate Finance and Appropriations committees are scheduled to report their budget proposals on "Budget Sunday," February 22, 2026, with each chamber expected to act on its budget by February 26.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] As of February 12, 2026, January general fund revenues were ahead of forecast by 2.9 percent, providing additional resources amid debates over spending priorities.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Controversies include Republican concerns over potential redirection of surpluses to partisan projects.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] After the regular session ended on March 14, 2026, without a budget bill passing, the General Assembly voted to convene for a special session on April 23, 2026, to continue negotiations.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The special session failed to produce a final bill, and, as of June 11, 2026, lawmakers are faced with a June 30th deadline to finalize the state's budget.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Negotiations remain stalled over several unresolved issues, including tax incentives for data centers.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] If the June 30th deadline passes, the state government will shut down, leading to uncertainty for agencies and local governments across Virginia.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The Democratic majorities advanced legislation aligned with campaign promises, including the "Affordable Virginia Agenda" focused on reducing costs in healthcare, housing, and energy.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] By February 9, 2026, more than half of these bills had passed either the House or Senate.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Republicans criticized some measures as increasing taxes and burdens on the middle class.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Constitutional amendments, under Virginia law, must be initiated by majorities in both houses in two consecutive legislatures before being sent to voters for approval.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] All four resolutions were passed by the House on January 14, 2026, and by the Senate on January 16, largely on party-line votes.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Governor Spanberger signed the bills on February 6, placing HJ4 on the April 21, 2026 Special Election ballot and the others on 2026 General Election on November 3, 2026.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Supporters argued the amendments protect essential rights, while opponents raised concerns over late-term abortions, human trafficking, parental consent, and potential gerrymandering in the redistricting measure.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Bills on solar siting reform (HB 359/SB 5) and public sector unionization (HB 582) also progressed.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] A bill to regulate cryptocurrency kiosks passed both chambers.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The redistricting amendment sparked debate over potential gerrymandering and suspension of anti-gerrymandering laws in the budget.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Legislation on "claim sharks" targeting veterans drew criticism for empowering predatory companies.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] A bill (HB 359) requiring private religious schools to participate in state assessments and affirm gender identities raised religious freedom concerns.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Data center pollution bills advanced amid environmental debates.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1961-united-states-state-legislative-elections] The **1961 United States state legislative elections** were held on November 7, 1961, for at least five state legislative chambers in at least three states.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1961-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats retained control of the New Jersey General Assembly and Republicans retained control of the New Jersey Senate.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1961-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats retained control of the Kentucky House of Representatives and of the Kentucky Senate.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1961-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Amelia Tucker, elected to the House, was the first Black woman to serve as a state legislator in Kentucky.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1961-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats retained control of the Virginia House of Delegates.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1961-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats won ninety-four of one hundred seats, a loss of two, Republicans won five, a gain of one, and an independent gained a seat.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1981-virginia-house-of-delegates-election] The **Virginia House of Delegates election of 1981** was held on Tuesday, November 3.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1981-virginia-house-of-delegates-election] Primary elections were held on September 8, 1981.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1981-virginia-house-of-delegates-election] The districts were established by the Assembly Act of August 11, 1981 (Acts of Assembly, 1981 Special Session, Chapter 5).
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1981-virginia-house-of-delegates-election] They were challenged in Federal District Court, which found the map unconstitutional in *Cosner v.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1981-virginia-house-of-delegates-election] The Court allowed the 1981 elections to proceed under the August 11, 1981 Act, but for a one-year term only.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1981-virginia-house-of-delegates-election] A new general election would thus be held in November 1982, under a new map.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1997-virginia-house-of-delegates-election] The **Virginia House of Delegates election of 1997** was held on Tuesday, November 4.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1997-virginia-house-of-delegates-election] The 1997 general election yielded a 51-48-1 Democratic majority.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1997-virginia-house-of-delegates-election] David Brickley resigned his seat right afterward, however, and a special election for District 51 was called.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1997-virginia-house-of-delegates-election] His seat flipped to the Republicans, and with Independent Lacey Putney siding with the Republicans, the chamber was tied.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1997-virginia-house-of-delegates-election] Democrats retained the Speakership through a power-sharing agreement.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1998-united-states-state-legislative-elections] The **1998 United States state legislative elections** were held on November 3, 1998, alongside other elections.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1998-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Elections were held for 86 legislative chambers in 46 states.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1998-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Despite hopes of winning a majority of state legislatures for the first time since 1954 after a decade of steady gains, Republicans only flipped two chambers in the Midwest while losing control of six.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1998-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats flipped five of those, while the Washington House of Representatives becoming tied.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1998-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans had also forced a tie in the Virginia House of Delegates and gained control of the Virginia Senate early in the year in special elections.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] The **1999 United States state legislative elections** were held on November 2, 1999, alongside other elections.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Elections were held for 7 legislative chambers in four states.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Both chambers of the Northern Mariana Islands legislature were up.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats maintained control of the Mississippi and Louisiana legislatures, while Republicans maintained control of the lower house in New Jersey and the upper house in Virginia.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans had won a 1997 special election to claim a 21-19 majority in the Virginia Senate after Democrat Charles L.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans maintained this majority in 1999, which gave them their first-ever elected majority in history.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans flipped the Virginia House of Delegates, which was previously tied, resulting in the first-ever Republican majority.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Additionally, in the summer of 1999, a Democratic senator died in the New Hampshire Senate and was succeeded by a Republican in a special election, switching that chamber from Democratic control to tied.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Regularly scheduled elections were held in 7 of the 99 state legislative chambers in the United States.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Nationwide, regularly scheduled elections were held for 538 of the 7,383 legislative seats.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] This table only covers regularly scheduled elections; additional special elections took place concurrently with these regularly scheduled elections.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All seats of the Louisiana State Senate and the Louisiana House of Representatives were up for election to four-year terms in single-member districts.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats maintained control of both chambers.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All seats of the Mississippi State Senate and the Mississippi House of Representatives were up for election to four-year terms in single-member districts.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats maintained control of both houses.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All seats of the New Jersey General Assembly were up for election.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Assembly members were elected to two-year terms in two-member districts.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All seats of the Senate of Virginia and the Virginia House of Delegates were up for election in single-member districts.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Senators were elected to four-year terms, while delegates served terms of two years.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans maintained control of the Senate and flipped the House of Delegates, which was previously tied.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All seats of the Northern Mariana Islands House of Representatives and half of the Northern Mariana Islands Senate are up for election.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Senators are elected to four-year terms, and Representatives are elected to two-year terms.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans maintained control of both houses.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Elections to state legislatures were held on November 7, 2000, simultaneously with the 2000 United States presidential election.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Elections were held for 86 legislative chambers in 44 states, simultaneous to those states' gubernatorial elections.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Election occurred in both chambers of each state's legislature, except for Alabama, Louisiana, Maryland, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Virginia.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Michigan held elections for the lower house.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Six territorial chambers in four territories and the District of Columbia were up as well.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] These elections determined the redistricting process after the 2000 census.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats won control of the Colorado Senate for the first time since 1963.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Additionally, a coalition government replaced the Republican-controlled Arizona Senate, and the Democratic-controlled Maine Senate became tied.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Regularly scheduled elections were held in 86 of the 99 state legislative chambers in the United States.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Nationwide, regularly scheduled elections were held for 6,015 of the 7,383 legislative seats.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Many legislative chambers held elections for all seats, but some legislative chambers that use staggered elections held elections for only a portion of the total seats in the chamber.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] The chambers not up for election either hold regularly scheduled elections in odd-numbered years, or have four-year terms and hold all regularly scheduled elections in presidential midterm election years.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Note that this table only covers regularly scheduled elections; additional special elections took place concurrently with these regularly scheduled elections.
[src:virginia-house-of-delegates/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Alaska House of Representatives and half of the Alaska Senate were up for election.
